, Scotland, United Kingdom","Wemyss, Fife, Scotland":"Wemyss, Fife, Scotland","Auchterhouse, Dundee, Angus, Skottland":"Dundee, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ramsay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant (the usual spelling in Scotland) of   Ramsey  . The Scottish Ramsays derive from Simund <i>de Ramesie</i>, recorded before 1175, who went to Scotland from Ramsey (Huntingdonshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ramsey","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish (Antrim): habitational name from Ramsey (Huntingdonshire, now part of Cambridgeshire), from Old English <i>hramsa</i> ‘wild garlic’ + <i>ēg</i> ‘island, low-lying land’. Alternatively, the name may also arise from Ramsey (Essex), probably from the same etymology as the Huntingdonshire placename. However, this is unlikely to be the source of the Scottish surname. This form of the surname is also common in Ireland, where it is probably in most if not all cases an altered form of Scottish   Ramsay  ."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margery Ramsay was born in 1324, in Auchterhouse, Forfarshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Henry Ramsay, was 24 and her mother, Ella House, was 22. She died in 1386, in East Wemyss, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1324–1386":"1324–1386","1332–Female":"1332–Surnud","1310–1332":"1310–1332","1300–1341":"1300–1341","1302–1338":"1302–1338","1338":"1338","9 January 1338":"9. jaanuar 1338","1324":"1324","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1332":"1332","1386":"1386","1341":"1341","1372":"1332","Kirkton of Auchterhouse, Du